[32m│[0m **thoughts:**                                                                [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m The application has a clear XSS vulnerability in the `/page` endpoint. The   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m input reflection mechanism was straightforward - the `name` parameter value  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m is placed directly into an HTML input element's value attribute without      [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m escaping double quotes. This allowed breaking out of the attribute context.  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m The key challenge was bypassing the quote filter - the application strips    [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m both single and double quotes from the input, preventing simple              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m `alert('XSS')` or `alert("XSS")` payloads. The solution was using            [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m `String.fromCharCode(88,83,83)` which dynamically constructs the string      [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m "XSS" in JavaScript without requiring quotes in the payload itself.          [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m The attack vector: `test" autofocus                                          [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m onfocus=alert(String.fromCharCode(88,83,83)) x="` works by:                  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 1. Closing the value attribute with `"`                                      [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 2. Adding `autofocus` to make the input auto-focus on page load              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 3. Adding `onfocus=alert(String.fromCharCode(88,83,83))` event handler that  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m fires when focused                                                           [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 4. Using `x="` to consume the trailing quote from the original HTML          [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m This is a classic attribute-based XSS with a quote filter bypass using       [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m JavaScript encoding.                                                         [32m│[0m
